Supervised and unsupervised learning with baseline scores and progression rates of markers from structural MRI and cognitive assessments¶

Project Work of Patric Wyss for the courses Data Science Fundamentals 1-5¶

1) Overview and set-up¶

1.1) Overview of the five different courses¶

This notebook contains analyses for the course work of the course data science fundamentals. It covers a data set of multiple longitudinally assessed markers from cogntively impaired patients (see below for more information). All courses 1-5 were heplful for this work, here a short overview

  • Modul 1: Basics needed in all parts (indexing, functions, ...)
  • Modul 2: Not used much of it. In future I will write own modules containing all the functions. Here I included the own functions when there were first used such that it is easier to follow what was done
  • Modul 3: Used in all parts of this course work (all data management with panda)
  • Modul 4: I implemented linear models and significance tests to examine differecnes in means between different patient groups
  • Modul 5: This was the main focus. On one hand I performed unsupervised approaches to exmaine structure in the data and reduce the dimensionality of the data. On the other hand, I was interested in predicting cognitive decline (regression) or clinical diagnoses (classification). Given the number of subjects and features as well as the time needed for training I did not implement all algorithms learned in this course. E.g., I focused on the libary "sklearn" and did not implement neural networks.

The main focus was: Finding the best underlying structure of the data (unsupervised) by using performance measures for the prediction of external criteria (cognitive decline, clinical diagnoses). I used the data with reduced dimensionality (with PCA, clustering) in supervised approaches and focussed on performance metrics for predicting the external criteria rather than performance measures based on the features used for unsupervised learning itself (e.g. explained variance in PCA)

Data¶

In my PhD project "Data-driven subject profiling and stageing in ageing and demenatia" we are focussing on the analyses of mutlivariate, repeatedly assessed markers. We used two publicly available data sets (ADNI and AIBL). One main directions is focussing on linear-mixed effects models for the analyses of multivariate, longituidnal data to predict latent variables covering the structure of the data, future response values or external criteria. We implemented a framwork for generative classification (Wyss et. all 2021). As in this study we are also using for this course work a data set consiting of subjects that start with the clinical label "Mild cogntive impairements" (MCI) and either stay with this label for at least 3 years or convert to the stadium Alzheimers dementia (AD) within a maximum of 3 years. We call this two groups of patients "MCI-stables" and "MCI-converters". In this course work we are using an implementation to predict subject-specific random intercepts and slopes in time (another implementation than in Wyss et al (2021)). These random effects are predicted using univariate, linear mixed-effects models. The model uses the age at first visit (baseline-age) and the time since baseline as independent variables to predict the marker values over time. Besides so called fixed-effects that can be used to predict population-level means, the model also include random effects that determine the variance-covariance structure. Moreover, within our cross-validation framwork the random effects can be predicted for given values of observed response values. The subject-specific (random) intercept in time is the deviation of the population-level intercept of a population with same baseline age. Hence, these intercepts are adjusted for ageing differnces in the markers given by their age at study entry. Subjects with positive values of the random intercepts have values above the average of the population of subjects with same baseline age (negative below average). The subject-specific (random slopes) in time are the random deviations of the slope in time of the marker from the population level slopes. We considered different markers, i.e. cognitive or biological from structural MRI. More precisely, we consider here the cognitive markers MMSE and RAVLT as well as volumes of regions of interest (have "H_MUSE" in the column name) and a summary score called SPARE-AD score. The SPARE-AD score quantifies how "AD-like" the structure of brain is.

With the code below the data frame is created. In the directory given by the object "path" there are multiple (27) files contaiing intercepts and slopes for different markers. We read them in and merge them into one file as follows

# Function to fit PCA and present the results
def pcaFitPlot(data, nrPc):
    # Fir PCA to data
    pca=PCA(n_components=nrPc)
    pca.fit(data)

    # print explained variances of PCs
    print(pca.explained_variance_ratio_)

    # plot explained variance
    plt.plot(pca.explained_variance_ratio_,'-o')
    plt.title('Scree plot')
    plt.ylabel('Percentage of explained variance')
    plt.grid()
    plt.show()

    return(pca)

# Function to fit PCA to two-dimensional data and visualize reconstruction on first PC
def plotReconstructPca2d(data_train, data_test, col):
    # Fit PCA to training data and represent results 
    # (see function pcaFitPlot)
    pca_train=pcaFitPlot(data_train, 2)

    # extract the scores on the PCAs for test data
    scores=pca_train.transform(data_test)
    
    # Compute reconstruction on first PC
    res=np.dot(scores[:,:1], pca_train.components_[:1,:]) 

    # Plot result
    plt.figure(figsize=((5,5)))
    plt.title('Reconstruction with first principal component')
    plt.plot(data_test[:,0],data_test[:,1],'o', c=col)
    plt.plot(res[:,0],res[:,1],'o', c="red")
    plt.grid()
    plt.show()

Functions¶

First we include our own functions for data analyses with clustering (will also be used in later sections)

In [9]:
def perfClust(data, meth, clustRange):
    # Initialize output, i.e. performances silhoutte score or AIC/BIC (for mixture of Gaussian)
    bic=[]
    sil=[]

    # loop over the consider range of number of clusters
    for nrClust in clustRange:

        # Initialize model either k means or mixture of Gaussian
        if meth=="kMeans":
            clustTemp = KMeans(n_clusters=nrClust, random_state=10)
        if meth=="GM":
            clustTemp =  GaussianMixture(n_components=nrClust, covariance_type='full')
        
        # Fit model on data
        clustTemp.fit(data)
        
        # predict cluster label for training set
        cluster_labels=clustTemp.predict(data)

        # compute silhoutte score for cluster solution
        score=silhouette_score(data, cluster_labels)

        # append it to the output object
        sil.append(score)

        # Compute AIC and BIC (only in case we use mixture of Gaussian)
        if meth=="GM":
            bic.append(clustTemp.bic(data))
   
    # plot results to choose best cluster solution
    plt.xlabel('Number of clusters')
    plt.ylabel('Silhouette score')
    plt.plot(np.arange(len(sil))+2, sil,'-o')
    plt.show()
    
    # return Siloutte score for k means
    if meth=="kMeans":
        return(sil)
    
    # Visualize AIC and BIC for mixture of Gaussian 
    # and return all performance measures
    if meth=="GM":

        plt.figure()
        plt.xlabel('Number of clusters')
        plt.ylabel('BIC')
        plt.plot(np.arange(len(bic))+2, bic,'-o')
        plt.show()
        return([sil, bic])

3) Supervised Learning¶

After exploring the data with unspupervised techniques I implemented in a next step supervised approaches to predict random effects of markers (regression) or the clinical diagnosis e.g. MCI-stables or MCI-converters (classification). On one hand we used the random-effects itself as featrures, on the other hand we also used reduced-feature spaces for predictions given either by PCA or clustering.

def sigTestLocation(valgroup1, valgroup2):
     #assumption: normal with same variances
        print("#-- Test normal")
        k1, p1 = stats.normaltest(valgroup1) 
        print("p-value group 1 = %1.2f" % p1)
        
        k2, p2 = stats.normaltest(valgroup2) 
        print("p-value group 2 = %1.2f" % p2)
        
        # t-Test means equal variance
        print("#-- t-Test equal variances")
        print(stats.ttest_ind(valgroup1, valgroup2, equal_var = True))
  
        # t-Test of means unequal variance
        print("#-- t-Test equal variances")
        print(stats.ttest_ind(valgroup1, valgroup2, equal_var = False))
        
        # mann withney test of location
        print("#-- Mann Withney")
        print(stats.mannwhitneyu(valgroup1, valgroup2))

# Function that fits different classifcation models (logistic regression, decsion tree, random forest and boosted trees) 
# on training data, makes prediction on a test set# and computes the performances of the classifiers
# Arguments: 
# pred_train        data containing features of the subject in the training set
# class_train       vector containing diagnoses of the subjects in the trainining set
# pred_test         data containing feautres of the subjects in the test set
# class_test        vector containing diagnoses of the subjects in the test set
# rangeDecTree      range of model complexitity for decision trees
# rangeRandForest   range of model complexitity for random forest
# rangeBoostTree    range of model compexitivy for boosted trees
def classPerfFun(pred_train, class_train, pred_test, class_test, rangeDecTree, rangeRandForest, rangeBoostTree):
    # Analyses with logistic regression
    print("#------logistic regression")
    print("")
    ## Fit model
    logReg=linear_model.LogisticRegression()
    logReg.fit(pred_train, class_train)

    ## Print performance
    print("training accuracy= %.3f" % logReg.score(pred_train,  class_train))
    print("test accuracy= %.3f" % logReg.score(pred_test, class_test))

    # Analyses with decision trees
    print("")
    print("#------Decision Tree")
    ## loop over the range of considered depths
    for depth in rangeDecTree:
        print(depth)

        ### Fit model
        decTree=tree.DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=depth)
        decTree.fit(pred_train, class_train)
        
        # Print performance
        print("training accuracy= %.3f" % decTree.score(pred_train, class_train))
        print("test accuracy= %.3f" % decTree.score(pred_test, class_test))
    
    # Analyses with random forest
    print("")
    print("#------Random Forest")
    
    ## loop over the range of considered number of estimators
    for n_est in rangeRandForest:
        print(n_est)

        ### Fit model
        randForest = ensemble.RandomForestClassifier(max_depth=4, n_estimators=n_est)
        randForest.fit(pred_train, class_train)
        
        ### Print performance
        print("training accuracy= %.3f" % randForest.score(pred_train, class_train))
        print("test accuracy= %.3f" % randForest.score(pred_test, class_test))
        
    # Analyses with boosted decision trees
    print("")
    print("#------Boosted Decision Trees")
    
    ## loop over the range of considered number of estimators
    for n_est in rangeBoostTree:
        print(n_est)

        ## Fit model
        boostTree = ensemble.GradientBoostingClassifier(max_depth=1, n_estimators=n_est)
        boostTree.fit(pred_train, class_train)
        
        # Print performance
        print("training accuracy = %.3f" % boostTree.score(pred_train, class_train))
        print("test accuracy= %.3f" % boostTree.score(pred_test, class_test))

# Function that fit cluster model with two clusters on training data, 
# makes prediction on test data and prints frequency table of cluster 
# assingments and real clinical diagnoses
# Arguments; 
# data_train        data containing features of the subject in the training set
# data_test         data containing feautres of the subjects in the test set
# class_test        vector containing diagnoses of the subjects in the test set
# meth               used method for clustering either "kMeans" or "GM"
def clustBinDiag(data_train, data_test, diag_test,meth):
    # Initialize model (k means or mixture of Gaussian)
    if meth=="kMeans":
        clust = KMeans(n_clusters=2, random_state=10)
    if meth=="GM":
        clust =  GaussianMixture(n_components=2, covariance_type='full')
    
    # Fit cluster model to the training data
    clust.fit(data_train)

    # Predict cluster labels for subjects in the test set
    cluster_labels=clust.predict(data_test)

    # Build and print frequency table cluster x diagnosis
    df_clust = pd.DataFrame({'clust':cluster_labels, 'Diagnosis':diag_test})
    df_clust_freq=df_clust.groupby(["clust", "Diagnosis"]).size()
    print(df_clust_freq)

    # return fitted cluster model
    return(clust)

# Function that fit PCA on training data, fits classification or regression models considering different number 
# of PCs on training data, makes prediction of PCs and diagnoses on test data and 
# prints and visualizes classification/regression performances.

# Arguments: 
# pred_train        data containing features of the subject in the training set
# resp_train        vector containing response values (continous or binary) of the subjects in the trainining set
# pred_test         data containing feautres of the subjects in the test set
# class_test        vector containing response values (continous or binary) of the subjects in the test set
# meth              the method of the supervised algorithm that is used
#                   "linear":       linear regression
#                   "logit":        logistic regression
#                   "randForest":   random forest
#                   "boost":        boosted decision trees
# pcaRange          range of considered number of chosen PCs
# param             Number of parameters used for supervised algorithms (None for linear and logistic regression)

def perfNrPcFct(pred_train, resp_train, pred_test, resp_test, meth, pcaRange, param=None, printRes=False):
    # Fit PCA on training data
    pcaModel=PCA(n_components=min(pred_train.shape))
    pcaModel.fit(pred_train)

    # Predict scores on all PCs (training and test set)
    pred_pca_train=pcaModel.transform(pred_train)
    pred_pca_test=pcaModel.transform(pred_test)

    # Initialize performance output object
    perf=[]

    # Loop over range of considered number of PCs
    for k in pcaRange:
        ## Extract given number of PCs
        if k==0:
            pred_train_pca_k=pred_pca_train[:,[k]]
            pred_test_pca_k=pred_pca_test[:,[k]]
        if k!=0:
            pred_train_pca_k=pred_pca_train[:,:k]
            pred_test_pca_k=pred_pca_test[:,:k]

        ## Fit supervised model on training data
        ### linear model 
        if meth=="linear":
            predModel = linear_model.LinearRegression()
            predModel.fit(pred_train_pca_k, resp_train)
        
        ### logistic model
        if meth=="logit":
            predModel = linear_model.LogisticRegression()
            predModel.fit(pred_train_pca_k, resp_train)
        
        ### random Forest
        if meth=="randForest":
           predModel = ensemble.RandomForestClassifier(max_depth=4, n_estimators=param)
           predModel.fit(pred_train_pca_k, resp_train)
        
        ### boosted trees
        if meth=="boost":
            predModel = ensemble.GradientBoostingClassifier(max_depth=1, n_estimators=param)
            predModel.fit(pred_train_pca_k, resp_train)
        
        if printRes:
            ## print performance
            print(k+1)
            print("training performance= %.3f" % predModel.score(pred_train_pca_k, resp_train))
            print("test performance= %.3f" % predModel.score(pred_test_pca_k, resp_test))

        ## Add performance in test set to list
        perf.append(predModel.score(pred_test_pca_k, resp_test))
    
    # Plot performance: 
    plt.xlabel('Numbers of PCs')
    plt.ylabel('Performance test set')
    plt.ylim([0, 1])
    plt.plot(pcaRange, perf,'-o')
    plt.show()

Using the data from the SPARE-AD Score only we performed different analyses covering the courses 4 (statistics, only in this section) and 5 (machine learning, also in all following sections).

simple linear regression¶

First, we fitted a simple linear regression with the random intercept of the MMSE (measuring the cognitive state at baseline) and the random intercept of the SPARE-AD score (measuring the typicality for AD of the structure of the brain). As in the course 4 of data science fundamentals (statistics) we are focusing here on the inferring of the effect between the two variables rather than out-of sample predictions for predictive analytics. Hence, here we fit the model on the whole data set.

# Compare location of random intercepts of SPARE-AD

#-- Test normal
p-value group 1 = 0.00
p-value group 2 = 0.07
#-- t-Test equal variances
Ttest_indResult(statistic=-17.222949213788603, pvalue=5.386145834722927e-54)
#-- t-Test equal variances
Ttest_indResult(statistic=-16.836999715335015, pvalue=1.4193159052547297e-50)
#-- Mann Withney
MannwhitneyuResult(statistic=12413.0, pvalue=3.222066666936042e-48)

Again, all three tests revealed significant difference. Of note, we did not make any p-value adustments for multiple comparisons. Given the size of the p-values (<<0.01) all p-values would also survive adjustments (e.g., Bonferonni) and remain significant.

Linear Models (Multiple linear Regression)¶

In a next step we built a model to predict the random slope in time of the MMSE as measure of (general) cognitive decline using both random effects of the SPARE-AD that quantify how AD-like the brain is in the beginning and how this change over time.

In [20]:
# Fit linear model with intercept on training data
reg_spareIct = linear_model.LinearRegression()

# Print performance

In the previous analyses with unsupervised approach we saw that the two-cluster solution was the best for the SPARE-AD features accoridng to diffferent performance measures for clustering (training and evaluation was on the same data). I a next step I examined how this assignments of the two-cluster solution correspond with the real clinical diagnoses which, importantly, where not used in training of the unsupervised model. To this end the function "clustBinDiag" was programmed that fits cluster model on training data (only features and no diagnoses), predict cluster assignments for subjects in the test-set and create frequency tables of the cluster assignment and the clinical diagnosis in the test set.

In [24]:
# k Means clustering
clustBinDiag(x_spare_train, x_spare_test, d_test, "kMeans")
print("Accuracy to predict diagnosis with cluster assignment", (95+65)/x_spare_test.shape[1])

# Mixture of Gaussian clustering model
random.seed(201813)
clustBinDiag(x_spare_train, x_spare_test, d_test, "GM")
print("Accuracy to predict diagnosis with cluster assignment", (90+68)/x_spare_test.shape[1])

clust  Diagnosis

       D1           81

       D1           12
dtype: int64
Accuracy to predict diagnosis with cluster assignment 80.0
clust  Diagnosis

       D1           81
1      D0           74
       D1           12
dtype: int64
Accuracy to predict diagnosis with cluster assignment 79.0

Hence, without knowing the diagnosis in training of the cluster models, 81 out of 104 patients of the cluster 0 are MCI-converters (diagnosis D1) and 77 out of 89 patients of cluster 1 have are MCI-stables. When using cluster assignment as prediction for the diagnosis we get the following classification accuracy:

In [25]:
print((81+77)/(23+81+77+12))

0.8186528497409327

This accuracy estimate is competitive to classifers of supervised algorithms that use the diagnosis during training.
